<tr><td><table role="presentation" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="background-color:#0F2237;">
<tr><td class="mp" style="padding:52px 56px 40px;text-align:center;">
  <p style="margin:0 0 14px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:9px;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:0.3em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.4);">A TENNIS LIFE &middot; WEEK 3 OF 9</p>
  <h1 class="ht" style="margin:0 0 8px;font-family:'Cormorant',Georgia,serif;font-weight:300;font-size:42px;line-height:1.08;color:#F5F0E5;">The <em style='font-style:italic;font-weight:400;color:#E8834A;'>Rise.</em></h1>
  <p style="margin:0;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:13px;font-weight:400;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.45);">From #24 to Blue Chip — the years that changed everything</p>
</td></tr></table></td></tr>
<tr><td class="mp" style="padding:36px 56px 0;"><p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15.5px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.85;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.68);">Hey %FIRSTNAME%,</p><p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15.5px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.85;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.68);">Last week I told you about my grandfather, the little court at Ford Park, and the family tree that made tennis feel inevitable. This week: the years when the game went from something I loved to something I was actually good at.</p></td></tr>
<tr><td class="mp" style="padding:24px 56px 0;">
<table role="presentation" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="background-color:#0F2237;border-radius:10px;">
<tr><td style="padding:28px 32px;">
  <p style="margin:0 0 12px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:9px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#E8834A;">TAGGING ALONG WITH MOM</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 12px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.75;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.65);">Through all of this — before, during, and alongside everything else — there was my mom. She was coaching high school tennis at Eisenhower in San Bernardino and working as a teaching pro at a community in Highland. She had a whole world there — students, adult clients, players at every level.</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 12px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.75;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.65);">I&rsquo;d just tag along. I&rsquo;d hit with her students. I&rsquo;d play matches with her adults while she was teaching. I&rsquo;d get on court with anyone who&rsquo;d have me. I&rsquo;d also spend hours down at the University of Redlands courts, just playing doubles or hitting with local players — whoever was around. <strong style='color:#F5F0E5;'>You couldn&rsquo;t get me off the court.</strong> I wasn&rsquo;t following a plan. I was just a kid who liked to hit.</p>
  <p style="margin:0;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.75;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.65);">That never really stopped. Even as I started training with coaches and competing in tournaments, I was still tagging along with my mom, still hitting with whoever was available, still stacking reps everywhere I could. That&rsquo;s how the foundation got built — not in one place, but in all of them.</p>
</td></tr></table></td></tr>
<tr><td class="mp" style="padding:16px 56px 0;">
  <p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15.5px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.85;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.68);">Then came Vijay Scatliffe — the first real competitive training group I&rsquo;d ever been part of. He ran serious sessions out at the park courts in San Bernardino, and his kids were legit — his son Malcolm went on to play at Penn State, his daughter Charlotte played at UCSB and went on to coach at the University of the Pacific. Other guys in the group were ranked well above me.</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15.5px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.85;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.68);">I started competing in tournaments at eleven years old. My first year, I was ranked #24 in the section. Same thing the second year of 12s — #24 again. I was solid, but I wasn&rsquo;t breaking through yet.</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15.5px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.85;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.68);">I&rsquo;d show up, get whooped, and come back the next day. Over and over. That was the whole pattern: get humbled, show up again, repeat.</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15.5px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.85;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.68);">I remember Vijay drilling me right before a sectional tournament — just grinding me into the ground as a warm-up — and then I went out and beat a kid who was top ten in SoCal. That was the first time I thought: <strong style="color:#1B3A5C;">I can actually do this.</strong></p>
</td></tr>
<tr><td class="mp" style="padding:24px 56px 0;">
<table role="presentation" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="background-color:#0F2237;border-radius:10px;">
<tr><td style="padding:28px 32px;">
  <p style="margin:0 0 12px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:9px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#E8834A;">WINNING OJAI</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 12px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.75;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.65);">The rankings were climbing fast. I went from #24 in the 12s to #4 in my first year of 14s. By my second year of 14s, I was #3 in Southern California. First year of 16s — #3. Second year of 16s — #3. First year of 18s — #3. I held that spot until I stopped playing junior tournaments at sixteen or seventeen to focus on the pro transition. By November 2004, I was #3 in SoCal, #12 nationally, and #5 on the TennisRecruiting Power Index. I was a <strong style='color:#F5F0E5;'>Blue Chip recruit</strong> — the highest classification in junior tennis recruiting — for most of my career.</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 12px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.75;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.65);">But the moment it felt real was April 2003. Fourteen years old. The Ojai Valley Tournament Boys&rsquo; 14s Singles Championship.</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 12px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.75;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.65);">If you&rsquo;re not familiar with the Ojai, it&rsquo;s one of the oldest and most respected tennis tournaments in the western United States — running since 1899. We played at Libby Park, right next to the Pac-10 Championships. My mom and my dad drove me. And in the finals, all the kids were there cheering. For a kid who&rsquo;d been stuck at #24 for two years and was just starting to break through, winning that title with my family watching — that meant everything.</p>
  <p style="margin:0;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.75;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.65);">The next year I went back in the 16s and made the final again. Back-to-back Ojai finals in consecutive age divisions. That told me I wasn&rsquo;t a fluke.</p>
</td></tr></table></td></tr>
<tr><td class="mp" style="padding:16px 56px 0;">
  <p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15.5px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.85;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.68);">That same year, I was playing #1 singles for Redlands High School — as a freshman. Our team went 23-2 and made it to the CIF Southern Section Division III Championship final.</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15.5px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.85;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.68);">In the championship match against Long Beach Poly, the team score was tied 9-9 on sets. It came down to total games won. We won it 81-79. A freshman, playing the top spot, and the whole thing decided by two games. That was one of the most memorable moments of my junior career.</p>
</td></tr>
<tr><td class="mp" style="padding:24px 56px 0;">
<table role="presentation" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="background-color:#0F2237;border-radius:10px;">
<tr><td style="padding:28px 32px;">
  <p style="margin:0 0 12px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:9px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#E8834A;">LEAVING HOME AT FIFTEEN</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 12px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.75;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.65);">After that breakout year, I earned a full scholarship to Advantage Tennis Academy at the Racquet Club of Irvine — only had to pay for food, which my parents and grandma covered. I moved second semester of my sophomore year. I wasn&rsquo;t scared. I was excited. This was my decision. Five hours of training a day. International players cycling through constantly. I won a SoCal Doubles Sectional Championship. I was selected for the Maze Cup team.</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 12px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.75;color:rgba(245,240,229,0.65);">Part of my scholarship deal was hitting with the paying clients — my way of earning my spot. As the academy grew, that meant more hitting sessions and less individualized coaching for me. By 18, I&rsquo;d stopped playing sectional and national tournaments to focus on the pro transition. When you stop playing the tournaments that feed your ranking, the number drops fast. <strong style="color:#2E8B8B;">That experience is why every player at LBTA gets coached. Not used. Coached.</strong></p>
</td></tr></table></td></tr>
<tr><td class="mp" style="padding:16px 56px 0;">
  <p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15.5px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.85;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.68);">Next week: The Stage — winning everything in SoCal, the biggest loss of my junior career, Kalamazoo, and the Orange Bowl.</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15.5px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.85;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.68);">Tennis, as it should be taught.</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 2px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:600;color:#1B3A5C;">Andrew</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:12px;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.5);">Founder &amp; Academy Director &middot; Laguna Beach Tennis Academy</p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:13px;font-weight:400;line-height:1.7;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.45);">Questions? Reach me directly: <a href="mailto:andrew@lagunabeachtennisacademy.com" style="color:#2E8B8B;font-weight:600;">andrew@lagunabeachtennisacademy.com</a> &middot; <strong style="color:#1B3A5C;">(949) 534-0457</strong></p>
  <p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:'DM Sans',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:1.75;color:rgba(27,58,92,0.45);">P.S. Speaking of the Mateljan tennis tree — my niece Emilija, the fifteen-year-old I mentioned in last week&rsquo;s email (ranked as high as #87 nationally, Class of 2029), was selected as a ball kid on stadium court at the BNP Paribas Open at Indian Wells last weekend. Out of a couple hundred ball kids, she was one of the few chosen for center court — and was picked for the interview on what the experience is like. Some of you were at Indian Wells and may have seen her out there. The next generation is already in the arena.</p>
</td></tr>
